                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.632/113: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Austria</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stockton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vienna</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-05-14T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 14, 1931—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received May 14—10:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>38. Received Department’s instruction No. 72 of April 30 with enclosures.</p>
                <p>I fear that exchange of ratifications might be jeopardized by note that I am
                    instructed to leave with Foreign Minister. Austrian Government is not anxious to
                    perfect this treaty. Because of the customs union which is projected between
                    Austria and Germany, the Austrian Government might welcome an opportunity to
                    escape with honor another treaty containing a most-favored-nation clause.
                    Schober stated in a speech last week that the most serious obstacle to the
                    reconstruction and restoration of Europe had been the most-favored-nation
                    clause.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stockton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
